<subSubSection lastPageId="30" lastPageNumber="31" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="29.[189,334,638,664]" box="[189,334,638,664]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,334,638,664]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,334,638,664]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[189,1399,685,747]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
Massive sponge (
<figureCitation box="[390,473,685,712]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="29.[189,232,1966,1992]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,856,1932]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[189,1398,855,1932]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="Fig. 16. Spheciospongia ndabazithe Samaai et al., 2019. A. Specimen PO52 in situ. B. The cut highlights the compact, darker choanosome. C. Tylostyles in different shapes. D. Spirasters variable in shapes." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3978543" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3978543/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
A–B), cup-shaped, light beige in the external and darker in the internal side. The alcohol preserved fragment is hard and incompressible, with a grey surface and a compact darker body.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[189,970,786,812]" box="[189,970,786,812]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">SKELETON. Ectosome and choanosome confused, rich in sediments.</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3978543" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3978543" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3978543/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" startId="29.[189,232,1966,1992]" targetBox="[189,1398,856,1932]" targetPageId="29">
<paragraph blockId="29.[189,1398,1966,2028]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,280,1966,1992]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 16.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Samaai et al., 2019" authorityName="Samaai" authorityYear="2019" box="[285,835,1966,1993]" class="Demospongiae" family="Clionaidae" genus="Spheciospongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hadromerida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="ndabazithe">
<emphasis box="[285,605,1966,1992]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Spheciospongia ndabazithe</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Samaai" box="[611,835,1966,1993]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Samaai" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="1 - 85" refId="ref21796" refString="Samaai T., Pillay R. &amp; Janson L. 2019. Shallow-water Demospongiae (Porifera) from Sodwana Bay, iSimangaliso Wetland Park, South Africa. Zootaxa 4587 (1): 1 - 85. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4587.1.1" type="journal article" year="2019">
Samaai 
<emphasis box="[703,752,1966,1992]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">et al</emphasis>
., 2019
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[844,865,1966,1992]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">A</emphasis>
. Specimen PO52 
<emphasis box="[1072,1143,1967,1992]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">in situ</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1156,1176,1966,1992]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">B</emphasis>
. The cut highlights the compact, darker choanosome. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[590,611,2001,2027]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">C</emphasis>
. Tylostyles in different shapes. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[984,1005,2002,2028]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">D</emphasis>
. Spirasters variable in shapes.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="30.[189,1399,267,427]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
SPICULES. Slim tylostyles sometimes curved towards the pointed tip (
<figureCitation box="[991,1098,267,294]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="29.[189,232,1966,1992]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,856,1932]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[189,1398,855,1932]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="Fig. 16. Spheciospongia ndabazithe Samaai et al., 2019. A. Specimen PO52 in situ. B. The cut highlights the compact, darker choanosome. C. Tylostyles in different shapes. D. Spirasters variable in shapes." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3978543" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3978543/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 16C</figureCitation>
), 250–(332)–410 μm×4– (7.3)–10 μm wide; sometimes they are modified in curved styles with acerate tips (
<figureCitation box="[1159,1266,301,328]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="29.[189,232,1966,1992]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,856,1932]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[189,1398,855,1932]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="Fig. 16. Spheciospongia ndabazithe Samaai et al., 2019. A. Specimen PO52 in situ. B. The cut highlights the compact, darker choanosome. C. Tylostyles in different shapes. D. Spirasters variable in shapes." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3978543" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3978543/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 16C</figureCitation>
); spirasters variable in shapes (
<figureCitation box="[416,523,334,361]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="29.[189,232,1966,1992]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,856,1932]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[189,1398,855,1932]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="Fig. 16. Spheciospongia ndabazithe Samaai et al., 2019. A. Specimen PO52 in situ. B. The cut highlights the compact, darker choanosome. C. Tylostyles in different shapes. D. Spirasters variable in shapes." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3978543" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3978543/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 16D</figureCitation>
) with an average length of 12.5 μm: C-shaped with many spines along the convex side, straight and smooth with groups of spines at the extremities and longer, S-shaped spirasters with spines scattered along the axis.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="30" pageNumber="31" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="30.[189,303,464,490]" box="[189,303,464,490]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,303,464,490]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,303,464,490]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[189,1399,509,569]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
Our specimen perfectly fits the species recently described from 
<collectingCountry box="[950,1101,509,535]" name="South Africa" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">South Africa</collectingCountry>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Samaai" box="[1148,1393,509,535]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Samaai" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" pagination="1 - 85" refId="ref21796" refString="Samaai T., Pillay R. &amp; Janson L. 2019. Shallow-water Demospongiae (Porifera) from Sodwana Bay, iSimangaliso Wetland Park, South Africa. Zootaxa 4587 (1): 1 - 85. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4587.1.1" type="journal article" year="2019">
Samaai 
<emphasis box="[1244,1304,509,535]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">et al.</emphasis>
(2019)
</bibRefCitation>
, with the exception of a larger variety of spirasters present in the specimen from Punta do Ouro.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
